1.2:
A type of textual content.

This is an enum of type Object so that these values are unforgeable.
Repeated attribute names and values. For example, dir="ltr" foo="bar" onclick="trustedFunction()" checked.
A CSS3 declaration, property, value or group of semicolon separated declarations.
A snippet of HTML that does not start or end inside a tag, comment, entity, or DOCTYPE; and that does not contain any executable code (JS, <object>s, etc.) from a different trust domain.

Executable Javascript code or expression, safe for insertion in a script-tag or event handler context, known to be free of any attacker-controlled scripts. This can either be side-effect-free Javascript (such as JSON) or Javascript that's entirely under Google's control.

Unsanitized plain-text content.

This is effectively the "null" entry of this enum, and is sometimes used to explicitly mark content that should never be used unescaped. Since any string is safe to use as text, being of ContentKind.TEXT makes no guarantees about its safety in any other context such as HTML.
A resource URI not under attacker control.
A properly encoded portion of a URI.
